vectorData.altText: 3. Which cell junctions are present at intercalated discs?
That’s right! Gap junctions, fascia adherens and desmosomes are ALL present at the intercalated discs of cardiac muscle.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Intercalated discs include gap junctions, which provide for intercellular communication and synchronization of contraction. 
Fascia adherens anchor the actin filaments of the terminal sarcomeres in adjacent cells to provide mechanical strength.
Desmosomes provide anchorage for intermediate filaments of the cytoskeleton, providing more mechanical strength between adjacent cells.
Pacemaker cells set the basic rate of contraction of the heart. The impulse is conducted between cells via the gap junctions at the intercalated discs. The rate of contraction is modulated by input from the autonomic nervous system and hormones.
